@node "Compatibility" "Compatibility"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Responsibility"
@{b}Compatibility@{ub}

KeepDays has a big possibility to work on earlier versions
than Xenolink 1.90+, the code for scanning filesections and 
deleting files hasn't changed that much.

KeepDays has so far been tested on the following computer
setups;

@{i}Amiga 1200@{ui}  68030/50MHz, 6 MB RAM, Kickstart 3.0/39.106,
            Workbench 3.0/39.29, Xenolink 1.95.
            Owned by author @{"TommyĀGreen" link "Author Info" 0}

@{i}Amiga 500@{ui}   68000/8MHz, 9 MB RAM, Kickstart 2.04/37.175,
            Workbench 2.1/38.28, Xenolink 1.90.
            Owned by author @{"TommyĀGreen" link "Author Info" 0}
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Documentation"
@prev "Compatibility"
@{b}Requirements@{ub}

KeepDays requires at least,
 
                            AmigaDOS 2.04/V37
                            approx. 4096 bytes stack
                            Xenolink 1.90+, earlier versions
                            could work also, see @{"compatibility" link "Compatibility" 0}
@endnode

@node "Documentation" "Documentation"
@next "Author Info"
@prev "Requirements"
@{b}Documentation@{ub}

KeepDays has a very simple usage, and I will not make this
documentation longer than it has be.

The program uses normal AmigaDOS 2.0 keyword parsing.

It accepts four different keywords:

D=DATE/K

Lets you specify which date you want to delete the files from.
KeepDays always deletes files older than the date set. The format
of the date is normal AmigaDOS date, DD-MMM-YY.


S=SECTIONS/K

Lets you specify what sections should be scanned for files to
delete. The format of the sections string is normal
Xenolink-format, 500-700,761,763-765.


NOP=NOPHYSICAL/S

Switch that lets you specify if you want the physical delete or
not. If set the physical file will remain unchanged.


TEST/S

Switch that runs KeepDays in test mode. It behaves just like in
normal mode except that it doesn't delete any files.

@{i}Example@{ui}

If you enter this string in Shell/CLI:

KeepDays Date 17-Sep-94 Sections 500 Test

the output might look like this in the Shell/CLI:

KeepDays v37.40 ®1994,1995 by Tommy Green

500. Databas
     BUTLERJAMES.LZX           17-Aug-94 Test only.
     FBASE106.LZX              17-Jul-94 Test only.
     SCATTERBRAIN11.LZX        29-Aug-94 Test only.

[Note] Keepdays was run in test mode, if TEST wasn't specified
these files would have been deleted.

@endnode

@node "Author Info" "Author Info"
@next "Acknowledgments"
@prev "Documentation"
@{b}Author information@{ub}

I'm 22 years old, born just south of Stockholm, Sweden in 1972.

I became interested in computers when my parents bought me a
Philips G7000 in the mid-80s.  8-)

Later I bought a C-128, a couple of years later I laid my hands on
my first Amiga, an Amiga 500 with Kickstart 1.3 (I still got it at
home, it served as BBS-computer until October 1994).

Did my military service from July 1993 to June 1994, in the
Swedish Air Force.

As mentioned I replaced my BBS-computer later on, with a A1200 and
a Blizzard A1230-II/50MHz card with four megabytes.

Right now I'm cooping with unemployment with 500,000 other people
here in Sweden.

I can be reached for bugreports and suggestions in XENOLINK_UTIL
as well as a netmail to 2:201/344.0.  
@endnode

